==Latin== [[File:Jupiter_Tonans.jpg|thumb|''Iuppiter Tonans'' (late first century statue)]]
===Alternative forms=== * [[Iupiter]]
===Etymology=== The main root {{term|Iovis|Iov-, Iovis|lang=la}} (cf. Old Latin ''Diovis'') is from {{etyl|ine-pro|la}} {{term/t|ine-pro|*dyew-||sky}} (whence also Latin {{term/t|la|diēs}}). Cognate with Ancient Greek {{term|sc=polytonic|Ζεύς|tr=Zeus|lang=grc}}, Hittite {{term|sc=unicode|𒅆𒍑|tr=sius|lang=hit}}, Sanskrit {{term|sc=Deva|द्यु|tr=dyú|lang=sa}}. The nominative {{term|Iuppiter|lang=la}} comes from a vocative combined with {{etyl|ine-pro|la}} {{term/t|ine-pro|*ph₂tḗr||father}} (whence also Latin {{term|pater|lang=la}}), and as such is cognate to Umbrian {{term|sc=Ital|𐌓𐌄𐌕𐌀𐌐𐌖𐌈|tr=iupater|lang=xum}}. The nominative form, essentially equivalent to ''Iovis Pater'', or "father Jove", is probably from an earlier *''Diu-pater'', and corresponds to a {{etyl|itc-pro|la}} root *''dyew-patēr'', from a Proto-Indo-European *''Dyēus ph₂ter'' ("sky father") (whence also Sanskrit {{l|sa|द्यौष्पितृ|tr=dyauṣ-pitṛ}}, Ancient Greek {{l|grc|Ζεύς πάτερ|Ζεῦ πάτερ|tr=Zeu pater}} ("o father Zeus")).
===Pronunciation=== * {{IPA|/ˈjup.pi.ter/|lang=la}} * {{audio|la-cls-Iuppiter.ogg|Audio (Classical)}}
